    <exercise xml:id="hyperbolicsine">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Compute the inverse of <m>f(x) = \dfrac{e^{x} - e^{-x}}{2}</m>.
          State the domain and range of both <m>f</m> and <m>f^{-1}</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <m>f^{-1}(x) = \ln\left(x + \sqrt{x^{2} + 1}\right)</m>.
          Both <m>f</m> and <m>f^{-1}</m> have domain
          <m>(-\infty, \infty)</m> and range <m>(-\infty, \infty)</m>.
        </p>
      </answer>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          In <xref ref="expfracinverse">Example</xref>,
          we found that the inverse of <m>f(x) = \dfrac{5e^{x}}{e^{x}+1}</m> was
          <m>f^{-1}(x) = \ln\left(\dfrac{x}{5-x}\right)</m> but we left a few loose ends for you to tie up.

          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Show that <m>\left(f^{-1} \circ f\right)(x) = x</m> for all <m>x</m> in the domain of <m>f</m> and that
                <m>\left(f \circ f^{-1}\right)(x) = x</m> for all <m>x</m> in the domain of <m>f^{-1}</m>.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                Find the range of <m>f</m> by finding the domain of <m>f^{-1}</m>.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                Let <m>g(x) = \dfrac{5x}{x+1}</m> and <m>h(x) = e^{x}</m>.
                Show that <m>f = g \circ h</m> and that
                <m>(g \circ h)^{-1} = h^{-1} \circ g^{-1}</m>. (We know this is true in general by <xref ref="fcircginverse">Exercise</xref>
                in <xref ref="InverseFunctions">Section</xref>,
                but it's nice to see a specific example of the property.)
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          With the help of your classmates,
          solve the inequality <m>e^{x} > x^{n}</m> for a variety of natural numbers <m>n</m>.
          What might you conjecture about the <q>speed</q>
          at which <m>f(x) = e^{x}</m> grows versus any polynomial?
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
  </subsection>
